{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Opioid painkillers are deadly, overprescribed and often ineffective.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by Prof Richard A Friedman contends opioid overdose epidemic is at heart of consistent rise in death rates for middle-aged white Americans since 1999; holds driver behind epidemic is enormous expansion of prescriptions for these drugs, on long-term basis, for chronic medical conditions as benign as low-back pain or sciatica; blames aggressive marketing by pharmaceutical industry of powerful and lucrative drugs like OxyContin; argues doctors must live up to their responsibility to help end epidemic by pushing back against seduction of drug industry.  ", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "4", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "FRIEDMAN", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Richard", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "A."}], "original": "By RICHARD A. FRIEDMAN"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/08/opinion/sunday/how-doctors-helped-drive-the-addiction-crisis.html", "lead_paragraph": "Opioid painkillers are deadly, overprescribed and often ineffective.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Doctors Enabling Addiction", "main": "How Doctors Helped Drive the Addiction Crisis", "content_kicker": "Contributing Op-Ed Writer", "kicker": "Op-Ed | Richard A. Friedman"}, "_id": "563e514038f0d85411acb1c0", "word_count": "952", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/11/08/opinion/sunday/08friedman/08friedman-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/11/08/opinion/sunday/08friedman/08friedman-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 648, "url": "images/2015/11/08/opinion/sunday/08friedman/08friedman-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/11/08/opinion/sunday/08friedman/08friedman-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "648"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "i